\begin_layout Plain Layout
Students have a hard time telling the difference between A|B and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

 on a problem where I ask given person is white, that ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basically translating english to math is hard...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using software you need to stop and think if the numbers are correct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I should introduce a continuous uniform distribution first and talk about
 the difference between a density function and a mass function.
 Then I can talk about the conditional stuff and claim that all the conditional/
independece rules hold for density functions as they do for mass functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More discussion about what an expectation is and why it is calculated the
 way that it is.
 Another example or two would be nice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some more examples of calculating stuff using the p-function.
 Maybe some pictures illustrating what you want, then writing it in math,
 then asking R for the answer.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to work out the mathematics of what we mean by probability.
 To begin with we first define an 
\emph on
outcome
\emph default
.
 An outcome is one observation from a random process or event.
 For example we might be interested in a single roll of a six-side die.
 Alternatively we might be interested in selecting one NAU student at random
 from the entire population of NAU students.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction to Set Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we jump into probability, it is useful to review a little bit of
 set theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Events
\emph default
 are properties of a particular outcome.
 For a coin flip, the event 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Heads
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be the event that a heads was flipped.
 For the single roll of a six-sided die, a possible event might be that
 the result is even.
 For the NAU student, we might be interested in the event that the student
 is a biology student.
 A second event of interest might be if the student is an undergraduate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Venn Diagrams
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be the set of all outcomes of my random trial.
 Suppose I am interested in two events 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The traditional way of representing these events is using a 
\emph on
Venn diagram.
\end_layout

