\begin_layout Section
Probability Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simple Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now take our Venn diagrams and use them to understand the rules of probabilit
y.
 The underlying idea that we will use is the the probability of an event
 is the 
\emph on
area
\emph default
 in the Venn diagram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Probability is the proportion of times an event occurs in many repeated
 trials of a random phenomenon.
 In other words, probability is the long-term relative frequency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact*
For any event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $0\le P(A)\le1$
\end_inset

 
\series default
since proportions always lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the set of all events that might occur, the area of our bounding rectangle
 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and the probability of event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 occurring will be the area in the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact*
If two events are mutually exclusive, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A\textrm{ \cup\ }B)=P(A)+P(B)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
def
\backslash
firstcircle{ (1.2,0) circle (1.5)} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
def
\backslash
secondcircle{(4.5,0) circle (1.5)}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% define edge and fill colors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
colorlet{edge}{blue!50} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
colorlet{area}{blue!20} 
\end_layout

