\begin_layout Example*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be the sum of two different colored dice.
 Suppose we are interested in 
\begin_inset Formula $P(S\le4)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the pair of dice can fall 36 different ways (6 ways for the
 first die and six for the second results in 6x6 possible outcomes, and
 each way has equal probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/36$
\end_inset

.
 Since the dice cannot simultaneously sum to 2 
\emph on
and 
\emph default
to 3, we could write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(S\le4) & = & P(S=2)+P(S=3)+P(S=4)\\
 & = & P(\left\{ 1,1\right\} )+P(\left\{ 1,2\right\} \mathrm{\textrm{ or }}\left\{ 2,1\right\} )+P(\{1,3\}\textrm{ or }\{2,2\}\textrm{ or }\{3,1\})\\
 & = & \frac{1}{36}+\frac{2}{36}+\frac{3}{36}\\
 & = & \frac{6}{36}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{6}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact*
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)+P(\bar{A})=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above statement is true because the probability of whole space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is one (remember S is all possible outcomes), then either we get an outcome
 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 occurs or we get an outcome in which 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not occur.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


