\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that fire claims are more likely fraudulent than auto or other
 claims.
 In fact, the proportion of fraudulent claims, given that the claim is against
 a fire policy is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(\textrm{ Fraud }|\textrm{ FirePolicy }) & = & \frac{\textrm{proportion of claims that are fire policies and are fraudulent}}{\textrm{proportion of fire claims}}\\
 & = & \frac{6\%}{20\%}\\
 & = & 0.3
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general we define conditional probability (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B)\ne0)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(A|B)=\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(B)}
\]

\end_inset

which can also be rearranged to show
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(A\cap B) & = & P(A\,|\, B)\, P(B)\\
 & = & P(B\,|\, A)\, P(A)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

since the order doesn't matter and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(A\cap B\right)=P\left(B\cap A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this rule, we might calculate the probability that a claim is an Auto
 policy given that it is not fraudulent.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(\, Auto\;|\; NotFraud\,\right) & = & \frac{P\left(\, Auto\;\cap\; NotFraud\right)}{P\left(\, NotFraud\,\right)}\\
\\
 & = & \frac{0.29}{0.9}\\
\\
 & = & 0.3\bar{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Two events 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are said to be 
\series bold
independent
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(A|B)=P(A)\;\;\textrm{and}\;\; P(B|A)=P(B)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What independence is saying that knowing the outcome of event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 doesn't give you any information about the outcome of event 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In simple random sampling, we assume that any two samples are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In cluster sampling, we assume that samples within a cluster are not independent
, but clusters are independent of each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are independent events, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(A\cap B) & = & P(A|B)P(B)\\
 & = & P(A)P(B)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose that we are interested in the relationship between the color and
 the type of car.
 Specifically I will divide the car world into convertibles and non-convertibles
 and the colors into red and non-red.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose that convertibles make up just 10% of the domestic automobile market.
 This is to say 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\; Convertable\;)=0.10$
\end_inset

.
 Of the non-convertibles, red is not unheard of but it isn't common either.
 So suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\; Red\;|\; NonConvertable\;)=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 However red is an extremely popular color for convertibles so let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\; Red\;|\; Convertable\;)=0.60$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

