\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

We can fill in some of the table using our the definition of conditional
 probability.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(Red\,\cap\, Convertable\right) & = & P\left(Red\,|\, Convertable\right)\, P\left(Convertable\right)\\
 & = & 0.60*0.10\\
 & = & 0.06
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Lets think about what this conditional probability means.
 Of the 
\begin_inset Formula $90\%$
\end_inset

 of cars that are not convertibles, 
\begin_inset Formula $15\%$
\end_inset

 those non-convertibles are red and therefore the proportion of cars that
 are red non-convertibles is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.90*0.15=0.135$
\end_inset

.
 Of the 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 of cars that are convertibles, 
\begin_inset Formula $60\%$
\end_inset

 of those are red and therefore proportion of cars that are red convertibles
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.10*0.60=0.06$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the total percentage of red cars is actually 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P\left(\, Red\,\right) & = & P\left(\; Red\;\cap\; Convertible\;\right)+P\left(\, Red\,\cap\, NonConvertible\,\right)\\
 & = & P\left(\, Red\,|\, Convertable\,\right)P\left(\, Convertible\,\right)+P\left(\, Red\,|\, NonConvertible\,\right)P\left(\, NonConvertible\,\right)\\
 & = & 0.60*0.10+0.15*0.90\\
 & = & 0.06+0.135\\
 & = & 0.195
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So when I ask for 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\; red\;|\; convertable\;)$
\end_inset

, I am narrowing my space of cars to consider only convertibles.
 While there percentage of cars that are red and convertible is just 6%
 of all cars, when I restrict myself to convertibles, we see that the percentage
 of this smaller set of cars that are red is 60%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Notice that because 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(Red\right)=0.195\ne0.60=P\left(Red\,|\, Convertable\right)$
\end_inset

 then the events 
\begin_inset Formula $Red$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Convertable$
\end_inset

 are not independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary of Probability Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & 0\le P\left(A\right)\le1\\
\\
 &  & P\left(A\right)+P\left(\bar{A}\right)=1\\
\\
P\left(A\cup B\right) & = & P\left(A\right)+P\left(B\right)-P\left(A\cap B\right)\\
\\
P\left(A\cap B\right) & = & \begin{cases}
P\left(A\,|\, B\right)P\left(B\right)\\
P\left(B\,|\, A\right)P\left(A\right)\\
P(A)P(B)\;\; & \textrm{ if A,B are independent}
\end{cases}\\
\\
P\left(A\,|\, B\right) & = & \frac{P\left(A\cap B\right)}{P\left(B\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discrete Random Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different types of probability distributions (and therefore your analysis
 method) can be divided into two general classes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuous Random Variables - the variable takes on numerical values and
 could, in principle, take any of an uncountable number of values.
 In practical terms, if fractions or decimal points in the number make sense,
 it is usually continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Discrete Random Variables - the variable takes on one of small set of values
 (or only a countable number of outcomes).
 In practical terms, if fractions or decimals points don't make sense, it
 is usually discrete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Presence or Absence of wolves in a State?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of Speeding Tickets received?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tree girth (in cm)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Photosynthesis rate?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction to Discrete Random Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following facts hold for discrete random variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The probability associated with every value lies between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sum of all probabilities for all values is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Probabilities for discrete RVs are additive.
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $P(3\textrm{ or }4)=P(3)+P(4)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Expected Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: Consider the discrete random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the sum of two fair dice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<fig.height=3, fig.width=6, echo=FALSE>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

x <- 2:12 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

y <- c(1:6,5:1)/36 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(x, y, col='blue', ylim=c(0,.18),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

      ylab='Probability', xlab='Sum',
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

      main='Distribution of the sum of two die')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

for(i in 1:length(x)){
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  lines(c(x[i],x[i]), c(0,y[i]), col='blue')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We often want to ask 'What is expected value of this distribution?' You
 might think about taking a really, really large number of samples from
 this distribution.
 We define the expected value (often denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

) as 
\emph on
a weighted average of the possible values and the weights are the proportions
 with which those values occur.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu=E[S] & = & \sum_{\textrm{possible }s}\; s\cdot P\left(S=s\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{s=2}^{12}s\cdot P(S=s)\\
\\
 & = & 2\cdot P\left(S=2\right)+3\cdot P\left(S=3\right)+\dots+11\cdot P\left(S=11\right)+12\cdot P\left(S=12\right)\\
 & = & 2\left(\frac{1}{36}\right)+3\left(\frac{2}{36}\right)+\dots+11\left(\frac{2}{36}\right)+12\left(\frac{1}{36}\right)\\
 & = & 7
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly we could define the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (which we often denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

) as 
\emph on
a weighted average of the squared-deviations that could occur.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma^{2}=V[S] & = & \sum_{s=2}^{12}\left(s-\mu\right)^{2}P(S=s)\\
 & = & (2-7)^{2}\left(\frac{1}{36}\right)+(3-7)^{2}\left(\frac{2}{36}\right)+\dots+(12-7)^{2}\left(\frac{1}{36}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{35}{6}=5.8\bar{3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We could interpret the expectation as the sample mean of an infinitely large
 sample, and the variance as the sample variance of the same infinitely
 large sample.
 These are two very important numbers that describe the distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
My wife is a massage therapist and over the last year, the number of clients
 she sees per work day (denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

) varied according the following table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\noindent
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
