</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}E_{2}F_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}F_{3}E_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}F_{2}F_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because these are far apart enough in space that the outcome of Trap1 is
 independent of Trap2 and Trap3, the 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(E_{1}\cap F_{2}\cap E_{3}) & = & P(E_{1})P(F_{2})P(E_{3})\\
 & = & (1-0.8)0.8(1-0.8)\\
 & = & 0.032
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\series bold
Notice how important the assumption of independence is!!! 
\series default
Similarly we could calculate the probabilities for the rest of the table.
\end_layout

