\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our small mammal example we can create a graph that shows the binomial
 distribution with the following R code:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<message=FALSE, fig.height=2.5, fig.width=5>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

library(mosaic)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plotDist('binom', size=3, prob=0.8, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

         main='Binomial Distribution(n=3,p=0.8)', 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

         ylab='Probability', xlab='Number of Full Traps')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

To calculate the height of any of these bars, we can evaluate the pmf at
 the desired point.
 For example, to calculate the probability the number of full traps is 2,
 we calculate the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(S=2) & = & {3 \choose 2}\left(0.8\right)^{2}\left(1-0.8\right)^{3-2}\\
\\
 & = & \frac{3!}{2!(3-2)!}(0.8)^{2}(0.2)^{3-2}\\
\\
 & = & \frac{3\cdot2\cdot1}{(2\cdot1)1}\;(0.8)^{2}(0.2)\\
\\
 & = & 3(0.128)\\
\\
 & = & 0.384
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can use R to calculate these probabilities.
 In general, for any distribution, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

d-function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 gives the distribution function (pmf or pdf).
 So to get R to do the preceding calculation we use:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# P( Y = 2 | n=3, pi=0.8 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

dbinom(2, size=3, prob=0.8)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expectation of this distribution can be shown to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E[Y] & = & \sum_{y=0}^{n}y\, P(Y=y)\\
\\
 & = & \sum_{y=0}^{n}y\;\frac{n!}{y!\left(n-y\right)!}\pi^{y}\left(1-\pi\right)^{n-y}\\
\\
 & = & \vdots\\
 & = & n\pi
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the variance can be similarly calculated
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V[Y] & = & \sum_{y=0}^{n}\left(y-E\left[Y\right]\right)^{2}\, P\left(Y=y|n,\pi\right)\\
\\
 & = & \sum_{y=0}^{n}\left(y-E\left[Y\right]\right)^{2}\;\frac{n!}{y!\left(n-y\right)!}\pi^{y}\left(1-\pi\right)^{n-y}\\
\\
 & = & \vdots\\
 & = & n\pi(1-\pi)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose a bird survey only captures the presence or absence of a particular
 bird (say the mountain chickadee).
 Assuming the true presence proportion at national forest sites around Flagstaff
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=0.1$
\end_inset

, then for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20$
\end_inset

 randomly chosen sites, the number of sites in which the bird was observed
 would have the distribution
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
