\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# P(Y=0) + P(Y=1) + P(Y=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

sum <- dbinom(0, size=20, prob=0.1) + 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

       dbinom(1, size=20, prob=0.1) + 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

       dbinom(2, size=20, prob=0.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# P(Y <= 2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

pbinom(2, size=20, prob=0.1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general we will be interested in asking four different questions about
 a distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the height of the probability mass function (or probability density
 function).
 For discrete variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 this is 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(Y=y\right)$
\end_inset

 for whatever value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 we want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the probability of observing a value less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

? In other words, to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(Y\le y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is a particular quantile of a distribution? For example, what value
 separates the lower 25% from the upper 75%?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Generate a random sample of values from a specified distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the probability distributions available in R are accessed in exactly
 the same way, using a 
\family typewriter
d-function
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
p-function
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
q-function
\family default
, and 
\family typewriter
r-function
\family default
.
 For the rest of this section suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a random variable from the distribution of interest and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is some possible value that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 could take on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
