\begin_layout Subsection
Poisson Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A commonly used distribution for count data is the Poisson.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of customers arriving over a 5 minute interval
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of birds observed during a 10 minute listening period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of prairie dog towns per 1000 hectares
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of alga clumps per cubic meter of lake water
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a RV is a Poisson RV if the following conditions apply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Two or more events do not occur at precisely the same time or in the same
 space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The occurrence of an event in a given period of time or region of space
 is independent of the occurrence of the event in a non overlapping period
 or region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected number of events during one period or region, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, is the same in all periods or regions of the same size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that these conditions hold for some count variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the the probability mass function is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(Y=y)=\frac{\lambda^{y}e^{-\lambda}}{y!}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the expected number of events over 1 unit of time or space and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $2.718281828$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E[Y] & = & \lambda\\
Var[Y] & = & \lambda
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose we are interested in the population size of small mammals in a region.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be the number of small mammals caught in a large trap (multiple traps in
 the same location?) in a 12 hour period.
 Finally, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim Poi(\lambda=2.3)$
\end_inset

.
 What is the probability of finding exactly 4 critters in our trap?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(Y=4) & = & \frac{2.3^{4}\, e^{-2.3}}{4!}\\
 & = & 0.1169
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

What about the probability of finding at most 4?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(Y\le4) & = & P(Y=0)+P(Y=1)+P(Y=2)+P(Y=3)+P(Y=4)\\
 & = & 0.1003+0.2306+0.2652+0.2033+0.1169\\
 & = & 0.9163
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
What about the probability of finding 5 or more?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(Y\ge5) & = & 1-P(Y\le4)\\
 & = & 1-0.9163\\
 & = & 0.0837
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

These calculations can be done using the distribution function (
\family typewriter
d-function
\family default
) for the poisson and the cumulative distribution function (
\family typewriter
p-function)
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<fig.height=3, fig.width=6>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plotDist('pois', lambda=2.3,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

         main='Poisson Distribution with lambda=2.3', ylab='density')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# P( Y = 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

dpois(4, lambda=2.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# P( Y <= 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ppois(4, lambda=2.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# 1-P(Y <= 4)  ==  P( Y > 4)  ==  P( Y >= 5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

1-ppois(4, 2.3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Continuous Random Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding the area under the curve of a particular density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 requires the use of calculus, but since this isn't a calculus course, we
 will resort to using R or tables of calculated values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uniform(0,1) Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you wish to draw a random number number between 0 and 1 and each
 number should have an equal chance of being selected.
 This random variable is said to have a 
\emph on
Uniform(0,1)
\emph default
 distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because there are an infinite number of rational numbers between 0 and 1,
 the probability of any particular number being selected is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\infty=0$
\end_inset

.
 But even though each number has 0 probability of being selected, some number
 must end up being selected.
 Because of this conundrum, probability theory doesn't look at the probability
 of a single number, but rather focuses on a 
\emph on
region of numbers
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make this distinction, we will define the distribution using a 
\emph on
probability density function
\emph default
 instead of the probability mass function.
 In the discrete case, we had to constrain the probability mass function
 to sum to 1.
 In the continuous case, we have to constrain the probability density function
 to integrate to 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<echo=FALSE, fig.height=4, fig.width=6>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

layout(matrix(1:2, nrow=2))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

par(mar=c(2,3,1,1))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

x <- seq(-.1, 1.1, length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

smallx <- seq(0, 1/3, length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(x, dunif(x, 0,1), type='l', ylab='f(x)', xlab='')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

polygon(x, dunif(x, 0, 1), col='grey')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(.5, .5, 'Area = 1')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

smallx <- seq(0, 1/3, length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(x, dunif(x, 0, 1), type='l', ylab='f(x)', xlab='')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

polygon(c(0, smallx, 1/3), c(0, dunif(smallx, 0,1), 0), col='grey')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(.15, .5, 'P(X < 1/3)')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(.15, .3, ' = 1/3'    )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding the area under the curve of a particular density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 usually requires the use of calculus, but since this isn't a calculus course,
 we will resort to using R or tables of calculated values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exponential Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponential distribution is the continuous analog of the Poisson distributio
n and is often used to model the time between occurrence of successive events.
 Perhaps we are modeling time between transmissions on a network, or the
 time between feeding events or prey capture.
 If the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has an Exponential distribution, its distribution function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
\lambda e^{-\lambda x} & x\ge0\;\textrm{ and }\;\lambda>0\\
0 & \textrm{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
