\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
Analogous to the discrete distributions, we can define the Expectation and
 Variance of these distributions by replacing the summation with an integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E[X] & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}x\, f(x)\, dx\\
 & = & \vdots\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\lambda}\\
Var[X] & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\left(x-E\left[X\right]\right)^{2}\, f\left(x\right)\, dx\\
 & = & \vdots\\
 &  & \frac{1}{\lambda^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the exponential distribution is defined by the rate of occurrence
 of an event, increasing that rate 
\emph on
decreases 
\emph default
the time between events.
 Furthermore since the rate of occurrence cannot be negative, we restrict
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Suppose the time between insect captures 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 during a summer evening for a species of bat follows a exponential distribution
 with capture rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=2$
\end_inset

 insects per minute and therefore the expected waiting time between captures
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda=1/2$
\end_inset

 minute.
 Suppose that we are interested in the probability that it takes a bat more
 than 1 minute to capture its next insect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $P(X>1)=$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
echo=FALSE, fig.height=4, fig.width=8
\end_layout

\end_inset

xsmall <- seq(1,5,length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(x, dexp(x, rate=2), lty=1, type='l', ylab='density')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

polygon(c(1, xsmall), c(0, dexp(xsmall, rate=2)), col='grey')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now must resort to calculus to find this area.
 Or use tables of pre-calculated values.
 Or use R (remembering that 
\family typewriter
p-functions
\family default
 give the area under the curve 
\emph on
to the left
\emph default
 
\emph on
of the given value.
\end_layout

