\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Normal Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Undoubtably the most important distribution in statistics is the normal
 distribution.
 If my RV 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is normally distributed with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, its probability distribution function is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}\exp\left[\frac{-(x-\mu)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp[y]$
\end_inset

 is the exponential function 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{y}$
\end_inset

.
 We could slightly rearrange the function to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}\exp\left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and see this distribution is defined by its expectation 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]=\mu$
\end_inset

 and its variance 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[X]=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice I could define it using the standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, and different software packages will expect it to be defined by one or
 the other.
 R defines the normal distribution using the standard deviation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
echo=FALSE, fig.height=5, fig.width=8
\end_layout

\end_inset

x <- seq(-5,7,length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(range(x), c(0,0.7), type='n', ylab='density', xlab='x')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(x, dnorm(x, mean=0, sd=1),   lty=1, lwd=2, col='black')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(x, dnorm(x, mean=2, sd=2),   lty=2, lwd=2, col='red')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(x, dnorm(x,     -3, sd=0.6), lty=3, lwd=2, col='blue')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

legend(2, .6, legend=c(
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  expression(paste(mu,'=0  ',sigma,'=1')),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  expression(paste(mu,'=2  ',sigma,'=2')),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  expression(paste(mu,'=-3  ',sigma,'=0.6'))),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

  lwd=2, lty=1:3, col=c('black','red','blue'))
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
It is known that the heights of adult males in the US is approximately normal
 with a mean of 5 feet 10 inches (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=70$
\end_inset

 inches) and a standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=3$
\end_inset

 inches.
 Your instructor is a mere 5 feet 4 inches (
\begin_inset Formula $64$
\end_inset

 inches).
 What proportion of the population is shorter than your professor?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
echo=FALSE, fig.height=5, fig.width=8
\end_layout

\end_inset

x <- seq(57,82,length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(x, dnorm(x, mean=70, sd=3), ylab='density', xlab='Adult Male Heights',
 type='l', lwd=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

x2 <- seq(57,64, length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

polygon(c(x2,64), c(dnorm(x2, mean=70, sd=3),0), col='grey')
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using R you can easily find this
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
echo=TRUE
\end_layout

\end_inset

# P( Y <= 64 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

pnorm(64, mean=70, sd=3)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
but unfortunately your professor may need to ask similar questions on an
 exam and so we have to talk about how to do the same calculation using
 a table.
 First we notice that the normal distribution is defined by the number of
 standard deviations from the mean (which we denote as 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

 and we note that he is 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 standard deviations from the mean because
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
z & = & \frac{64-70}{3}\\
 & = & \frac{-6}{3}\\
 & = & -2
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Next we look at the table in the front of the book for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=-2.00$
\end_inset

.
 To do this we go down to the 
\begin_inset Formula $-2.0$
\end_inset

 row and over to the 
\begin_inset Formula $.00$
\end_inset

 column and find 
\begin_inset Formula $0.0228$
\end_inset

.
 Only slightly over 2% of the adult male population is shorter!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How tall must a male be to be taller than 
\begin_inset Formula $80\%$
\end_inset

 of the rest of the male population? To answer that we must use the table
 in reverse and look for the 
\begin_inset Formula $0.8$
\end_inset

 value.
 We find the closest value possible (
\begin_inset Formula $0.7995)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 value associated with it is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.84$
\end_inset

.
 Next we solve the standardizing equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
z & = & \frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\\
0.84 & = & \frac{x-70}{3}\\
x & = & 3(0.84)+70\\
 & = & 72.49\;\textrm{inches}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Alternatively we could use the quantile function for the normal distribution
 
\family typewriter
(q-function)
\family default
 in R and avoid the imprecision of using a table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

qnorm(.8, mean=0, sd=1)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x & = & 3(0.8416)+70\\
 & = & 72.52\;\textrm{inches}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirical Rule - It is from the normal distribution that the empirical rule
 from chapter 3 is derived.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(\mu-\sigma\le X\le\mu+\sigma) & = & P(-1\le Z\le1)\\
 & = & P(Z\le1)-P(Z\le-1)\\
 & \approx & 0.8413-0.1587\\
 & = & 0.6826
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Flex Chunk
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fig.height=4, fig.width=8, echo=FALSE
\end_layout

\end_inset

z <- seq(-3,3,length=1000)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(z, dnorm(z), ylab='density', xlab='Z', type='l', lwd=2, main='Empirical
 Rule')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(c(-1,1), rep(dnorm(1),2), lwd=2, col=1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(c(-2,2), rep(dnorm(2),2), lwd=2, col=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

eps <- 0.015
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(0, dnorm(1)+ eps, expression(paste(''%~~%'','68%')), col=1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(0, dnorm(1)-eps, expression(paste(''%+-%'', '1', sigma)), col=1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(0, dnorm(2)+eps, expression(paste(''%~~%'','95%')), col=2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

text(0, dnorm(2)-eps, expression(paste(''%+-%'', '2', sigma)), col=2)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

